citeinfo.title: Alaska Contours, 1:1,000,000

descript.abstract:
The Alaska Department of Natural Resources (ADNR) has combined hypsography for several Digital Chart of the World (DCW) tiles into one coverage. Some edits to the data were made, which allowed ADNR to label high elevation points and mountain tops from the DCW data. The coverage contains elevation contours at every 1,000 feet. The hypsography used for statewide map products is often depicted as a contour line at every 3,000 feet, which offers visualization of vertical control as it relates to the other map features.
The hypsography data were combined from the HYPOINT and HYNET coverages comprising the following 5 degree by 5 degree tiles for Alaska:
AK 12,22,23,32,33 AL 21,31,32 BK 12,13,22,23,33 BL 11,12,13,21,22,23,31,32,33 CK 12,23,33 CL 11,12,13,21,22,23,31 DK 12,13,22,23 ZK 22,32

overview.eaover:
Excerpts from the DCW Documentation: The primary source of the DCW is the US Defense Mapping Agency (DMA) Operational Navigation Chart (ONC) series.
HYLNVAL - Contains the elevation value of the contour line in feet above mean sea level, as indicated on the ONC's. Absence of an elevation value is indicated by the number 99999. When contour lines for different elevations become coincident, such as in areas of steep topography, the single contour assigend the value for the highest elevation. Valid codes range from -1,000 feet to 29,000 feet incrementing by 1,000 feet.
HYLNTYPE DEFINITION -------- ---------- 1 Closed land contour 2 Depression contour 3 Closed land contour, approximate 4 Carrying contour, where two or more contour lines with different values coalesce 5 Depression contour, approximate 8 Connector (an arbitrary connector of the contour network, used for areas or lines of discontinuities such as road cut and fill situations - not for gaps due to elevation value labels. This connection was made by ESRI to establish a network so that elevation ranges are polygons that can be shaded or to correct errors in contours.) 9 None (outer boundary) 88 Used in situations during the edgematching process where differences and the automation module boundary is used for closure.
